WEBVTT

00:01.480 --> 00:03.920
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:04.580 --> 00:07.200
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:08.040 --> 00:13.340
For more information on how to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:13.900 --> 00:15.540
This is Jean O'Sullivan.

00:16.100 --> 00:19.720
The book is Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson.

00:19.960 --> 00:21.360
This is Chapter 31.

00:21.940 --> 00:22.960
The Treasure Hunt.

00:23.420 --> 00:24.420
Flint's Pointer

00:25.600 --> 00:28.560
Jim, said Silver, when we were alone,

00:28.920 --> 00:32.740
If I saved your life, you saved mine, and I'll not forget it.

00:33.320 --> 00:35.880
I seen the doctor waving you to run for it,

00:36.040 --> 00:37.940
With the tail of my eye I did,

00:38.100 --> 00:41.000
And I seen you say, No plane is hearing.

00:41.560 --> 00:43.180
Jim, that's one to you.

00:43.700 --> 00:48.160
This is the first glint of hope I had since the attack failed,

00:48.340 --> 00:49.860
And I owe it to you.

00:50.100 --> 00:53.580
And now, Jim, we're to go in for this here treasure hunting

00:53.580 --> 00:56.960
With sealed orders, too, and I don't like it,

00:57.040 --> 01:02.300
And you and me must stick close, back to back-like,

01:02.540 --> 01:05.500
And we'll save our next spite of fate and fortune.

01:06.720 --> 01:10.220
Just then a man hails from the fire that breakfast was ready,

01:10.440 --> 01:15.000
And we were soon seated here and there about the sand over biscuit and fried junk.

01:15.480 --> 01:17.680
They had lit a fire to roast an ox,

01:17.920 --> 01:21.640
And it was now grown so hot that they could only approach it from the windward,

01:21.640 --> 01:24.380
And even there, not without precaution.

01:24.880 --> 01:26.600
In the same wasteful spirit,

01:27.040 --> 01:30.760
They had cooked, I suppose, three times more than we could eat,

01:31.080 --> 01:35.620
And one of them, with an empty laugh, threw what was left into the fire,

01:35.900 --> 01:39.340
Which blazed and roared again over this unusual fuel.

01:39.960 --> 01:44.320
I never in my life saw men so careless of the morrow.

01:44.660 --> 01:48.660
Hand to mouth is the only word that can describe their way of doing,

01:48.660 --> 01:52.100
And what with wasted food and sleeping sentries,

01:52.220 --> 01:55.220
Though they were bold enough for a brush and be done with it,

01:55.540 --> 02:00.340
I could see their entire unfitness for anything like a prolonged campaign.

02:01.460 --> 02:05.460
Even Silver, eating away with Captain Flint upon his shoulder,

02:05.820 --> 02:08.020
Had not a word of blame for their recklessness,

02:08.320 --> 02:10.240
And this the more surprised me,

02:10.400 --> 02:14.400
For I thought he had never shown himself so cunning as he did then.

02:15.160 --> 02:17.340
Aye, mates, said he,

02:17.460 --> 02:22.040
It's lucky you have barbeque to think for you with this herehead.

02:22.720 --> 02:25.220
I got what I wanted, I did, sure enough.

02:25.400 --> 02:28.680
They have the ship. Where they have it, I don't know yet,

02:28.740 --> 02:32.740
But once we hit the treasure, we'll have to jump about and find out.

02:33.000 --> 02:38.040
And then, mates, us that has the boats, I reckon, has the upper hand.

02:38.720 --> 02:42.620
Thus he kept running on with his mouth full of the hot bacon,

02:42.620 --> 02:45.040
Thus he restored their hope and confidence,

02:45.460 --> 02:49.320
And, I more than suspect, repaired his own at the same time.

02:50.200 --> 02:54.980
As for hostage, he continued, that's his last talk, I guess,

02:55.080 --> 02:59.240
With them that love so dear, I've got my piece of news,

02:59.280 --> 03:02.900
And thank you to him for that, but it's over and done.

03:03.740 --> 03:06.340
I'll take him in a line when we go treasure hunting,

03:06.920 --> 03:11.640
For we'll keep him like so much gold in case of accidents, you mark,

03:11.640 --> 03:16.320
And in the meantime, once we got the ship and treasure both,

03:16.780 --> 03:19.080
And off to sea like jolly companions,

03:19.980 --> 03:22.900
Why, then, we'll talk Mr. Hawkins over, we will,

03:23.260 --> 03:26.940
And we'll give him his share, to be sure, for all his kindness.

03:27.940 --> 03:31.540
It was no wonder the men were in good humour now.

03:31.840 --> 03:34.880
For my part, I was horribly cast down.

03:35.360 --> 03:39.180
Should the scheme he had now sketched prove feasible,

03:39.180 --> 03:44.320
Silver, already doubly a traitor, would not hesitate to adopt it.

03:44.840 --> 03:47.100
He had still a foot in either camp,

03:47.100 --> 03:51.300
And there was no doubt he would prefer wealth and freedom with the pirates

03:51.300 --> 03:53.460
To a bare escape from hanging,

03:53.740 --> 03:56.780
Which was the best he had to hope on our side.

03:57.560 --> 04:00.640
Nay, and even if things so fell out,

04:00.700 --> 04:03.960
That he was forced to keep his faith with Dr. Livesey,

04:03.960 --> 04:06.580
Even then, what danger lay before us!

04:06.580 --> 04:08.820
What a moment that would be

04:08.820 --> 04:11.920
When the suspicions of his followers turned to certainty,

04:12.320 --> 04:14.700
And he and I should have to fight for dear life,

04:15.000 --> 04:20.500
He a cripple and I a boy, against five strong and active seamen.

04:20.600 --> 04:22.860
Add to this double apprehension the mystery

04:22.860 --> 04:25.460
That still hung over the behaviour of my friends,

04:25.820 --> 04:27.980
Their unexplained desertion of the stockade,

04:28.340 --> 04:30.480
Their inexplicable session of the chart,

04:30.660 --> 04:35.040
Or, harder still to understand, the doctor's last warning to Silver.

04:35.040 --> 04:37.560
Look out the squalls when you find it,

04:37.800 --> 04:39.520
And you will readily believe

04:39.520 --> 04:42.380
How little taste I found in my breakfast,

04:42.820 --> 04:46.480
And with how uneasy a heart I set forth behind my captors

04:46.480 --> 04:48.000
On the quest for treasure.

04:49.000 --> 04:52.760
We made a curious figure, had anyone been there to see us,

04:53.120 --> 04:57.360
All in soiled sailor clothes and all but me armed to the teeth.

04:57.800 --> 04:59.860
Silver had two guns slung about him,

05:00.020 --> 05:01.700
One before and one behind,

05:02.020 --> 05:03.940
Besides the great cutlass at his waist,

05:03.940 --> 05:06.920
And a pistol in each pocket of his square-tailed coat.

05:07.420 --> 05:09.320
To complete this strange appearance,

05:09.720 --> 05:12.080
Captain Flint sat perched upon his shoulder,

05:12.860 --> 05:15.700
And gabbling odds and ends of purposeless sea-talk.

05:16.320 --> 05:18.260
I had a line about my waist,

05:18.320 --> 05:20.740
And followed obediently after the sea-cook,

05:21.100 --> 05:22.860
Who held the loose end of the rope,

05:23.120 --> 05:26.420
Now in his free hand, now between his powerful teeth.

05:26.700 --> 05:29.940
For all the world I was led like a dancing bear.

05:30.240 --> 05:32.100
The other men were variously berthened,

05:32.100 --> 05:34.280
Some carrying picks and shovels,

05:34.280 --> 05:37.000
For that had been the very first necessary

05:37.000 --> 05:39.340
They brought ashore from the Hispaniola,

05:39.640 --> 05:43.560
Others laden with pork, bread, and brandy for the midday meal.

05:43.980 --> 05:46.980
All the stores, I observed, came from our stock,

05:47.220 --> 05:51.060
And I could see the truth of Silver's words the night before.

05:51.640 --> 05:53.760
Had he not struck a bargain with the doctor,

05:54.060 --> 05:56.520
He and his mutineers, deserted by the ship,

05:56.940 --> 05:59.520
Must have been driven to subsist on clear water

05:59.520 --> 06:01.120
In the proceeds of their hunting.

06:01.120 --> 06:04.040
Water would have been little to their taste,

06:04.320 --> 06:06.800
A sailor is not usually a good shot,

06:06.920 --> 06:09.820
And besides all that, when they were so short of eatables,

06:10.180 --> 06:13.100
It was not likely they would be very flush of powder.

06:13.760 --> 06:16.380
Well, thus equipped, we all set out,

06:16.520 --> 06:18.140
Even the fellow with the broken head,

06:18.480 --> 06:20.500
Who certainly should have kept in shadow,

06:20.800 --> 06:23.620
And straggled, one after another, to the beach,

06:23.920 --> 06:25.580
Where the two gigs awaited us.

06:25.920 --> 06:29.000
Even these bore trace of the drunken folly of the pirates,

06:29.000 --> 06:30.680
One in a broken thwart,

06:30.960 --> 06:33.400
And both in their muddy and unbailed condition,

06:33.940 --> 06:36.820
Both were to be carried along with us for the sake of safety,

06:37.100 --> 06:39.660
And so, with our numbers divided between them,

06:39.900 --> 06:42.380
We set forth upon the bosom of the anchorage.

06:43.260 --> 06:46.640
As we pulled over, there was some discussion on the chart.

06:46.980 --> 06:51.680
The Red Cross was, of course, far too large to be a guide,

06:51.980 --> 06:54.800
And the terms of the note on the back, as you will hear,

06:55.360 --> 06:57.180
Admittedly of some ambiguity.

06:57.180 --> 07:00.560
They ran, the reader may remember, thus,

07:01.520 --> 07:09.500
Tall tree, spy-glass shoulder, bearing a point to the N of N-N-E,

07:09.880 --> 07:15.820
Skeleton island, E-S-E, and by E, ten feet.

07:17.380 --> 07:19.820
A tall tree was thus the principal mark.

07:19.860 --> 07:23.640
Now, right before us, the anchorage was bounded by a plateau

07:23.640 --> 07:27.320
From two to three hundred feet high, adjoining on the north

07:27.320 --> 07:30.200
The sloping southern shoulder of the spy-glass,

07:30.660 --> 07:33.200
And rising again toward the south to the rough,

07:33.360 --> 07:35.720
Cliffy eminence called Mizenmast hill.

07:36.100 --> 07:39.400
The top of the plateau was dotted thickly with pine trees

07:39.400 --> 07:40.380
Of varying height.

07:40.800 --> 07:43.940
Every here and there, one of a different species,

07:44.240 --> 07:47.200
Rose forty or fifty feet clear above its neighbors,

07:47.500 --> 07:50.460
And which of these was the particular tall tree

07:50.460 --> 07:53.640
Of Captain Flint, could only be decided on the spot

07:53.640 --> 07:55.420
And by readings of the compass.

07:55.660 --> 07:59.440
Yet, although that was the case, every man on board the boats

07:59.440 --> 08:02.860
Had picked a favorite of his own, ere we were half way over,

08:03.160 --> 08:06.000
Long John alone, shrugging his shoulders and bidding them

08:06.000 --> 08:07.600
Wait till they were there.

08:08.380 --> 08:12.820
We pulled easily by Silver's directions, not to weary the hands

08:12.820 --> 08:16.980
Primiturally, and after quite a long passage, landed at the mouth

08:16.980 --> 08:20.360
Of the second river, that which runs down a woody cleft

08:20.360 --> 08:21.360
Of the spy-glass.

08:21.860 --> 08:25.760
Thence, bending to our left, we began to ascend the slope

08:25.760 --> 08:27.120
Towards the plateau.

08:27.720 --> 08:31.720
At the first outset, heavy, miry ground and a matted,

08:31.900 --> 08:34.300
Marish vegetation greatly delayed our progress,

08:34.600 --> 08:37.760
But by little and little the hill began to steepen

08:37.760 --> 08:41.520
And become stony underfoot, and the wood to change its character

08:41.520 --> 08:43.540
And to grow in a more open order.

08:43.820 --> 08:47.520
It was, indeed, a most pleasant portion of the island

08:47.520 --> 08:48.760
That we were now approaching.

08:48.760 --> 08:52.520
A heavy-scented broom and many flowering shrubs

08:52.520 --> 08:54.720
Had almost taken the place of grass.

08:55.160 --> 08:58.780
Thickets of green nutmeg trees were dotted here and there

08:58.780 --> 09:02.040
With the red columns and the broad shadow of the pines,

09:02.060 --> 09:05.800
And the first mingled their spice with the aroma of the others.

09:06.220 --> 09:10.240
The air, besides, was fresh and stirring, and this,

09:10.440 --> 09:13.860
Under the sheer sunbeams, was a wonderful refreshment

09:13.860 --> 09:14.880
To our senses.

09:15.500 --> 09:18.240
The party spread itself abroad, in a fan-shape,

09:18.240 --> 09:20.120
Shouting and leaping to and fro.

09:20.440 --> 09:22.720
About the centre and a good way behind the rest,

09:23.080 --> 09:25.860
Silver and I followed, I tethered by my rope,

09:26.080 --> 09:29.240
He ploughing with deep pants among the sliding gravel.

09:29.740 --> 09:32.960
From time to time, indeed, I had to lend him a hand,

09:33.220 --> 09:36.380
Or he must have missed his footing and fallen backward down the hill.

09:37.160 --> 09:39.720
We had thus proceeded for about half a mile

09:39.720 --> 09:41.820
And were approaching the brow of the plateau

09:41.820 --> 09:44.620
When the man upon the farthest left began to cry aloud,

09:44.700 --> 09:45.540
As if in terror.

09:45.960 --> 09:47.520
Shout after shout came from him,

09:47.520 --> 09:49.860
And the others began to run in his direction.

09:50.180 --> 09:52.720
He can't have found the treasure, said old Morgan,

09:52.860 --> 09:55.860
Hurrying past us from the right, for that's clean atop.

09:56.100 --> 09:58.560
Indeed, we found when we also reached the spot

09:58.560 --> 10:00.080
It was something very different.

10:00.540 --> 10:04.460
At the foot of a pretty big pine and involved in a green creeper,

10:04.520 --> 10:07.820
Which had even partly lifted some of the smaller bones,

10:08.120 --> 10:12.140
A human skeleton lay, with a few shreds of clothing on the ground.

10:12.700 --> 10:16.180
I believe a chill struck for a moment to every heart.

10:17.520 --> 10:21.940
He was a seaman, said George Mary, who, bolder than the rest,

10:22.020 --> 10:25.140
Had gone up close and was examining the rags of clothing.

10:25.960 --> 10:28.820
Least ways, this is good sea-cloth.

10:29.560 --> 10:31.800
Aye, aye, said Silver, like enough.

10:32.460 --> 10:34.480
You wouldn't look to find a bishop here, I reckon.

10:35.020 --> 10:39.440
But what sort of a way is that for bones to lie?

10:40.080 --> 10:41.120
Taint in nature!

10:42.040 --> 10:45.920
Indeed, on a second glance, it seemed impossible to fancy

10:45.920 --> 10:48.040
That the body was in a natural position.

10:48.580 --> 10:51.940
But for some disarray, the work perhaps of the birds

10:51.940 --> 10:55.200
That had fed upon him, or of the slow-growing creeper

10:55.200 --> 10:57.500
That had gradually enveloped his remains,

10:58.040 --> 11:02.080
The man lay perfectly straight, his feet pointing in one direction,

11:02.460 --> 11:05.380
His hands raised above his head like a diver's,

11:05.500 --> 11:07.420
Pointing directly in the opposite.

11:07.820 --> 11:11.780
I've taken a notion into my old numb skull, observed Silver.

11:11.780 --> 11:13.160
Here's the compass.

11:13.700 --> 11:16.600
There's the tip-top point of Skeleton Island

11:16.600 --> 11:17.960
Sticking out like a tooth.

11:18.620 --> 11:21.960
Just take a bearing, will you, along the line of them bones.

11:22.680 --> 11:23.720
It was done.

11:23.980 --> 11:27.040
The body pointed straight in the direction of the island,

11:27.180 --> 11:32.980
And the compass read duly, E, S, E, and by E.

11:33.540 --> 11:35.340
I thought so, cried the cook.

11:35.700 --> 11:36.920
This here is a pointer.

11:37.180 --> 11:41.080
Right up there is our line for the Pole Star and the Jolly Dollars,

11:41.080 --> 11:44.520
But by thunder if it don't make me cold inside to think of Flint.

11:44.960 --> 11:48.040
This was one of his jokes, and no mistake.

11:48.440 --> 11:50.280
Him and these six was alone here.

11:50.300 --> 11:51.880
He killed them every man.

11:52.120 --> 11:55.480
And this one he hauled here and laid down by compass.

11:55.660 --> 11:56.840
Shiver me, Timbers.

11:57.340 --> 11:59.900
They're long bones and the hair's been yellow.

12:00.760 --> 12:02.940
Ay, that would be Allardus.

12:04.280 --> 12:06.420
You mind Allardus, Tom Morgan?

12:07.480 --> 12:09.560
Ay, ay, returned Morgan.

12:09.560 --> 12:10.960
I mind him.

12:11.260 --> 12:12.800
He owed me money, he did.

12:13.220 --> 12:15.240
And took my knife ashore with him.

12:16.040 --> 12:17.800
Speaking of knives, said another,

12:18.020 --> 12:19.700
Why don't we find his lying around?

12:20.200 --> 12:22.280
Flint weren't the man to pick a seaman's pocket,

12:22.520 --> 12:24.880
And the birds, I guess, would leave it be.

12:25.800 --> 12:28.960
By the powers that's true, cried Silver.

12:29.520 --> 12:33.000
There ain't a thing left here, said Mary,

12:33.060 --> 12:35.360
Still feeling around among the bones.

12:35.720 --> 12:38.540
Not a copper doot or a becky box.

12:38.540 --> 12:41.600
It don't look natural to me.

12:42.000 --> 12:44.260
No, by gum it don't, agreed Silver.

12:44.360 --> 12:48.440
Not natural, nor not nice, says you.

12:48.440 --> 12:50.220
Great guns, mess mates.

12:50.760 --> 12:54.360
But if Flint was living, this would be a hot spot for you and me.

12:54.960 --> 12:57.180
Six they were, and six are we,

12:57.300 --> 12:59.800
And bones is what they are now.

13:00.680 --> 13:04.280
I saw him dead with these here dead lights, said Morgan.

13:04.820 --> 13:05.840
Billy took me in.

13:05.840 --> 13:09.640
There he laid with penny pieces on his eyes.

13:09.800 --> 13:12.480
Did I? Sure enough, he's dead and gone below,

13:12.680 --> 13:14.180
Said the fellow with the bandage.

13:14.600 --> 13:18.020
But if ever a spirit walked, it would be Flint's.

13:18.160 --> 13:21.420
Dear heart, but he died bad, did Flint.

13:22.440 --> 13:24.460
I, that he did, observed another.

13:24.900 --> 13:27.820
Now he raged, and now he hollered for the rum,

13:28.080 --> 13:29.460
And now he sang.

13:30.160 --> 13:33.040
Fifteen men were his only songmates,

13:33.040 --> 13:37.460
And I tell you true, I never rightly liked to hear it since.

13:37.880 --> 13:40.780
It was main hot, and the windy was open,

13:40.940 --> 13:44.880
And I hear that old song coming out as clear as clear,

13:45.080 --> 13:47.340
And the death-hall on the man already.

13:47.780 --> 13:50.760
Come, come, said Silver, stow this talk.

13:51.080 --> 13:53.120
He's dead, and he don't walk.

13:53.440 --> 13:56.100
That I know least ways he won't walk by day.

13:56.860 --> 13:58.680
And you may lay to that.

13:59.460 --> 14:00.780
Care killed a cat.

14:00.780 --> 14:02.680
Fetch a head for the doubloons.

14:03.480 --> 14:06.540
We started certainly, but in spite of the hot sun

14:06.540 --> 14:09.640
And the staring daylight, the pirates no longer

14:09.640 --> 14:12.020
Ran separate and shouting through the wood,

14:12.440 --> 14:15.820
But kept side by side and spoke with bated breath.

14:16.340 --> 14:20.420
The terror of the dead buccaneer had fallen on their spirits.

14:30.780 --> 14:31.600
Thanks for watching.

